{
  "id": "019d31af-3e73-7aa2-8096-3e3e8be00a1c",
  "content": "# Tiered Knowledge: MCP Tools + CLI Commands (Issue #24)\n\n## Implementation Summary\n\nAdded the user-facing control plane for tiered knowledge lifecycle management:\n\n### MCP Tools (3 new, total 21)\n- `corvia_pin` (Tier 1): Pin entry by ID with agent audit trail. Requires agent_id via param or _meta.agent_id.\n- `corvia_unpin` (Tier 2/LowRisk): Unpin with confirmation. Makes entry eligible for GC demotion again.\n- `corvia_inspect` (Tier 1): Full lifecycle metadata — tier, retention_score, memory_type, access history, pin state, inbound edges.\n\n### CLI Commands (6 new)\n- `corvia gc status/run/history`: Operator observability for knowledge GC\n- `corvia pin/unpin/inspect`: Entry lifecycle management\n\n### Architecture Decisions\n- Pin is Tier 1 (additive/protective, no confirmation needed). Unpin is Tier 2 (removes safety guardrail).\n- CLI `unpin` requires `--yes` flag for consistency with MCP confirmation.\n- `GcKnowledgeHistory` is an in-memory ring buffer (50 entries) — ephemeral, lost on restart.\n- Pin/unpin use `update_entry_metadata` (whole-entry write). Known RMW race with concurrent access tracking — matches existing GC pattern, deferred to buffered-write refactor (#12).\n- Pin is idempotent: re-pinning overwrites previous pin info (last pinner wins).\n\n### Known Limitations (deferred)\n- `corvia gc run` CLI triggers knowledge GC; MCP `corvia_gc_run` triggers staging GC — naming collision to resolve in follow-up.\n- Periodic background GC cycles are not recorded in `GcKnowledgeHistory` — only manual triggers via REST.\n- Pin/unpin kernel ops downcast to LiteStore; PostgresStore not yet supported.\n- REST endpoints have no authentication gate (local-first assumption).\n\nPR: chunzhe10/corvia#51",
  "source_version": "mcp",
